[1
Date: Thu, 5 Aug 1999 11:05:44 +0200
From: Oliver.Schmetzer@t-online.de (Oliver Schmetzer)

I want to give you further information on the case of haemorrhagic fever in
Germany. In the German TV/newspapers the case was described like this:
On TV they told the German public it could be a case of Ebola or Lassa, and
results of tests will be available today. The patient is aged 39, he
currently lies in a ward in the Virchow-Klinik in Berlin called
Sonderisolierstation. This is a special [isolation ward constructed for
patients infected with dangerous microorganisms. He flew back to
Frankfurt/Oder and went on to airport Berlin/Tegel. He arrived there from a
journey to Elfenbeinkuste (Ivory Coast) in Africa.
Yesterday the man was described as being very ill, but you can talk to him.
He had internal bleeding [according to Norbert Suttorp, director of the
Infectious Disease Clinic of Virchow-Klinik. The man shot some film for 2
weeks and returned on Sunday. He felt ill and was taken to a German hospital
in Frankfurt/Oder. On Tuesday he was brought to Berlin. The ward 59 in
Berlin which I described has an air filtering system and no personnel from
this ward can leave it.
--
Oliver Schmetzer
Subscriber to the ProMED-mailing list
Bayreuth, Germany
Oliver.Schmetzer@t-online.de
