Date: 5 Aug 1999
From: Martin Hugh-Jones <mehj@mail.vetmed.lsu.edu>
& "M. Cosgriff" <mcosgriff@hotmail.com>
Source: The Times, London 5 Aug 1999 [edited
http://www.the-times.co.uk/news/pages/Times/frontpage.html?3173168

Fears of Ebola virus outbreak in Europe
-----------------------------------------
[Byline: Roger Boyes
Germany was on Ebola fever alert yesterday after a man returned from a trip
to Africa bleeding through his eyes and ears.
Ebola, which is one of the most infectious and deadly viruses, killing up to
80 per cent of its victims, is virtually unkown in the West.
The patient, a 40-year-old German citizen, returned from a business trip in
the Ivory Coast at the weekend. He travelled via Zurich on Swissair to
Berlin and the German authorities are trying to track down passengers who
may have had contact with him. The infected man was accompanied by his wife,
who is now in quarantine, as is their child.
The whole of the Virchow Clinic quarantine unit has been cleared for Olaf U.
Doctors and nurses are wearing airtight safety uniforms reminiscent of the
film
Outbreak, which depicted the dangers of a virus such as Ebola.
The hospital said the clinic would need 2 more days of laboratory tests to
determine whether the illness -- identified only as a "viral haemorrhagic
fever" - was
Ebola or the less dangerous but highly infectious Lassa fever.
Until then the hospital was taking the precautions normally associated with
an Ebola outbreak. The patient was taken to hospital by helicopter to avoid
ground contact.
In Berne last night, Swissair confirmed that [the passenger had caught its
flight from Abidjan with 188 passengers on board. Airline executives had
decided not to contact any of the passengers unless doctors in Berlin
determined it was Ebola.
--
[Hemorrhagic fevers have never been transmitted through the air to other
people. When a passenger seriously ill with Ebola virus flew from Gabon to
South Africa & died in hspital there, neither of his 2 companions or any
other passengers caught it (see: Ebola - South Africa (02) 961117184708) -
Mod.JW
